This paper is about dialogue models, which are commonly studied in the field of natural language processing (NLP) and specifically in the subfield of computational linguistics (CL). Therefore, cs.CL is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes new models that promote diversity and relevance in dialogue generation, which involves machine learning techniques such as reinforcement learning (RL), and optimization of loss functions, which are studied in the subfields of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper uses a metric to evaluate the diversity of generated responses, which is a statistical measure, and thus falls under the subfield of statistics (cs.SD). Finally, the paper also involves neural networks, which are studied in the subfield of neural engineering (cs.NE).
